column2: 1. Mobile app privacy is about a user’s right to exercise control over decisions about how their information is collected, used, and shared.
column3: 2. User control of personal information is essential to mobile app privacy.
column4: 3. I believe that mobile app privacy is compromised when the user loses control over their information as a result of app usage.
column5: 4. I’m not concerned that smartphone apps are collecting too much personal information about me.
column6: 1. Mobile app developers seeking information should disclose the way the data are collected, processed, and used.
column7: 2. A good mobile app privacy policy should have a clear and conspicuous disclosure.
column8: 3. It is very important to me that I am aware and knowledgeable about how my personal information will be used.
column9: 1. It usually bothers me when smartphone apps ask me for personal information.
column10: 2. When mobile apps ask me for personal information, I sometimes think twice before providing it.
column11: 3. It bothers me to give personal information to so many mobile apps.
column12: 4. I’m concerned that smartphone apps are collecting too much personal information about me.
column13: 1. Mobile apps should not use personal information for any purpose unless it has been authorized by the individuals who provided information.
column14: 2. When people give personal information to a mobile app for some reason, the app developer should never use the information for any other reason.
column15: 3. Mobile app developers should never sell the personal information in their computer databases to other companies.
column16: 4. Mobile app developers should never share personal information with other companies unless it has been authorized by the individual who provided the information.
